name: no relation
description: there is no relation between the two entities
example: Banana and beef are no relation.

name: country
description: sovereign state of this item (not to be used for human beings)
example: Greenland is an autonomous territory of Denmark.

name: located in the administrative territorial entity
description: the item is located on the territory of the following administrative entity. Use P276 for specifying locations that are non-administrative places and for items about events. Use P1382 if the item falls only partially into the administrative entity.
example: Paris is located in the Île

name: country of citizenship
description: the object is a country that recognizes the subject as its citizen
example: Elon Musk has South African citizenship.

name: contains administrative territorial entity
description: (list of) direct subdivisions of an administrative territorial entity
example: Los Angeles County contains the city of Los Angeles.

name: publication date
description: date or point in time when a work was first published or released
example: The book To Kill a Mockingbird was published in 1960.

name: performer
description: actor, musician, band or other performer associated with this role or musical work
example: Ed Sheeran performed 'Photograph' at tonight's concert.

name: date of birth
description: date on which the subject was born
example: Albert Einstein was born on March 14, 1879.

name: date of death
description: date on which the subject died
example: Isaac Newton died on March 31, 1727.

name: cast member
description: actor in the subject production [use "character role" (P453) and/or "name of the character role" (P4633) as qualifiers] [use "voice actor" (P725) for voice-only role]
example: Tom Hanks was a cast member in the movie Forrest Gump.

name: record label
description: brand and trademark associated with the marketing of subject music recordings and music videos
example: Sony Music Entertainment is a record label that has produced Beyoncé and Adele.

name: has part
description: part of this subject; inverse property of "part of" (P361). See also "has parts of the class" (P2670).
example: A car has parts such as an engine and wheels.

name: part of
description: object of which the subject is a part (if this subject is already part of object A which is a part of object B, then please only make the subject part of object A). Inverse property of "has part" (P527, see also "has parts of the class" (P2670)).
example: The heart is part of the human body.

name: country of origin
description: country of origin of this item (creative work, food, phrase, product, etc.)
example: Toyota is a company from Japan.

name: place of birth
description: most specific known (e.g. city instead of country, or hospital instead of city) birth location of a person, animal or fictional character
example: Newton was born in England.

name: inception
description: date or point in time when the subject came into existence as defined
example: The company Apple was founded on April 1, 1976.

name: member of sports team
description: sports teams or clubs that the subject represents or represented
example: Lionel Messi is a member of FC Barcelona.

name: member of political party
description: the political party of which this politician is or has been a member or otherwise affiliated
example: Joe Biden is a member of the Democratic Party.

name: member of
description: organization, club or musical group to which the subject belongs. Do not use for membership in ethnic or social groups, nor for holding a political position, such as a member of parliament (use P39 for that).
example: The European Union is a member of the United Nations.

name: sibling
description: the subject and the object have the same parents (brother, sister, etc.); use "relative" (P1038) for siblings-in-law (brother-in-law, sister-in-law, etc.) and step-siblings (step-brothers, step-sisters, etc.)
example: Prince William and Prince Harry are siblings.

name: child
description: subject has object as child. Do not use for stepchildren
example: Prince William and Prince Harry are children of Princess Diana.

name: continent
description: continent of which the subject is a part
example: France lies in the west of Europe.

name: author
description: main creator(s) of a written work (use on works, not humans); use P2093 when Wikidata item is unknown or does not exist
example: J.K. Rowling is the author of the Harry Potter series.

name: present in work
description: this (fictional or fictionalized) entity or person appears in that work as part of the narration (use P2860 for works citing other works, P361/P1433 for works being part of other works, P1343 for entities described in non-fictional accounts)
example: Harry Potter is present in the work "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone".

name: applies to jurisdiction
description: the item (institution, law, public office, public register...) or statement belongs to or has power over or applies to the value (a territorial jurisdiction: a country, state, municipality, ...)
example: The U.S. Constitution applies to the jurisdiction of the United States.

name: educated at
description: educational institution attended by subject
example: Stephen Hawking was educated at the University of Cambridge.

name: spouse
description: the subject has the object as their spouse (husband, wife, partner, etc.). Use "unmarried partner" (P451) for non-married companions
example: Bill Gates is married to Melinda Gates.

name: conflict
description: battles, wars or other military engagements in which the person or item participated
example: India and Pakistan have erupted in a territorial conflict.

name: director
description: director(s) of film, TV-series, stageplay, video game or similar
example: Christopher Nolan directed the movie Inception.

name: headquarters location
description: city, where an organization's headquarters is or has been situated. Use P276 qualifier for specific building
example: Apple's headquarters are located in Cupertino, California.

name: father
description: male parent of the subject. For stepfather, use "stepparent" (P3448)
example: Barack Obama's father is Barack Obama Sr.

name: platform
description: platform for which a work was developed or released, or the specific platform version of a software product
example: The game was developed for the PlayStation platform.

name: participant of
description: event in which a person or organization was/is a participant; inverse of P710 or P1923
example: John was a participant of the marathon.

name: located in or next to body of water
description: sea, lake, river or stream
example: Sydney is located next to the Pacific Ocean.

name: owned by
description: owner of the subject
example: Instagram is owned by Facebook.

name: creator
description: maker of this creative work or other object (where no more specific property exists)
example: Stan Lee is the creator of Spider

name: developer
description: organisation or person that developed the item
example: Microsoft is the developer of the Windows operating system.

name: place of death
description: most specific known (e.g. city instead of country, or hospital instead of city) death location of a person, animal or fictional character
example: Mozart died in Vienna.

name: languages spoken, written or signed
description: language(s) that a person or a people speaks, writes or signs, including the native language(s)
example: John speaks English and Spanish fluently.

name: follows
description: immediately prior item in a series of which the subject is a part [if the subject has replaced the preceding item, e.g. political offices, use "replaces" (P1365)]
example: Barack Obama follows George W. Bush as the President of the United States.

name: league
description: league in which team or player plays or has played in
example: The Los Angeles Lakers are a team in the NBA.

name: participant
description: person, group of people or organization (object) that actively takes/took part in an event or process (subject).  Preferably qualify with "object has role" (P3831). Use P1923 for participants that are teams.
example: Serena Williams was a participant in the 2021 Australian Open.

name: head of government
description: head of the executive power of this town, city, municipality, state, country, or other governmental body
example: Joe Biden is the head of the U.S. government.

name: employer
description: person or organization for which the subject works or worked
example: Google is the employer of Sundar Pichai.

name: location
description: location of the object, structure or event. In the case of an administrative entity as containing item use P131. For statistical entities use P8138. In the case of a geographic entity use P706. Use P7153 for locations associated with the object.
example: The Louvre Museum is located in Paris, France.

name: followed by
description: immediately following item in a series of which the subject is a part [if the subject has been replaced, e.g. political offices, use "replaced by" (P1366)]
example: George W. Bush is followed by Barack Obama as the President of the United States.

name: characters
description: characters which appear in this item (like plays, operas, operettas, books, comics, films, TV series, video games)
example: Harry Potter and Ron Weasley are characters in the Harry Potter series.

name: award received
description: award or recognition received by a person, organisation or creative work
example: Meryl Streep has received three Academy Awards.

name: legislative body
description: legislative body governing this entity; political institution with elected representatives, such as a parliament/legislature or council
example: The United States Congress is the legislative body of the U.S. government.

name: publisher
description: organization or person responsible for publishing books, periodicals, printed music, podcasts, games or software
example: The publisher of "Game of Thrones" is Bantam Books.

name: religion
description: religion of a person, organization or religious building, or associated with this subject
example: The Taj Mahal is an Islamic architectural marvel.

name: notable work
description: notable scientific, artistic or literary work, or other work of significance among subject's works
example: The Mona Lisa is a notable work of Leonardo da Vinci.

name: original network
description: network(s) or service(s) that originally broadcasted a radio or television program
example: The TV show Breaking Bad aired on the AMC network.

name: screenwriter
description: person(s) who wrote the script for subject item
example: Aaron Sorkin is the screenwriter of The Social Network.

name: head of state
description: official with the highest formal authority in a country/state
example: Queen Elizabeth II is the head of state of the United Kingdom.

name: series
description: series which contains the subject
example: The Eternal Life of Death is the final book of the Three

name: located on terrain feature
description: located on the specified (geo)physical feature. Should not be used when the value is only political/administrative (P131) or a mountain range (P4552).
example: Mount Everest is located on the Himalayan mountain range.

name: producer
description: person(s) who produced the film, musical work, theatrical production, etc. (for film, this does not include executive producers, associate producers, etc.) [for production company, use P272, video games - use P178]
example: Steven Spielberg produced the movie Jurassic Park.

name: official language
description: language designated as official by this item
example: Spanish is an official language in Mexico.

name: military branch
description: branch to which this military unit, award, office, or person belongs, e.g. Royal Navy
example: The United States Army is a military branch of the U.S. government.

name: instance of
description: that class of which this subject is a particular example and member
example: The Eiffel Tower is an instance of a tower.

name: mouth of the watercourse
description: the body of water to which the watercourse drains
example: The Mississippi River flows into the Gulf of Mexico at its mouth.

name: start time
description: time an item begins to exist or a statement starts being valid
example: The Super Bowl starts at 6:30 PM EST.

name: operator
description: person, profession, or organization that operates the equipment, facility, or service
example: NASA is the operator of the International Space Station.

name: point in time
description: time and date something took place, existed or a statement was true
example: The first moon landing occurred on July 20, 1969.

name: founded by
description: founder or co-founder of this organization, religion or place
example: Facebook was founded by Mark Zuckerberg.

name: composer
description: person(s) who wrote the music [for lyricist, use "lyrics by" (P676)]
example: Beethoven composed the Symphony of Destiny.

name: manufacturer
description: manufacturer or producer of this product
example: Apple is the manufacturer of the iPhone.

name: parent organization
description: parent organization of an organization, opposite of subsidiaries (P355)
example: YouTube is a subsidiary of Google, which is the parent organization.

name: work location
description: location where persons or organisations were actively participating in employment, business or other work
example: John's work location was in downtown Manhattan.

name: capital
description: seat of government of a country, province, state or other type of administrative territorial entity
example: Tokyo is the capital of Japan.

name: dissolved, abolished or demolished
description: point in time at which the subject (organisation, building) ceased to exist;  see "date of official closure" (P3999) for closing a facility, "service retirement" (P730) for retiring equipment,  "discontinued date" (P2669) for stopping a product
example: The Berlin Wall was demolished in 1989.

name: subsidiary
description: subsidiary of a company or organization; generally a fully owned separate corporation. Compare with "business division" (P199). Opposite of parent organization (P749).
example: YouTube is a subsidiary of Google.

name: genre
description: creative work's genre or an artist's field of work (P101). Use main subject (P921) to relate creative works to their topic
example: Science fiction is a popular genre of literature.

name: original language of work
description: language in which a film or a performance work was originally created. Deprecated for written works and songs; use P407 ("language of work or name") instead.
example: The original language of Don Quixote is Spanish.

name: production company
description: company that produced this film, audio or performing arts work
example: The production company for this film was Warner Bros.

name: ethnic group
description: subject's ethnicity (consensus is that a VERY high standard of proof is needed for this field to be used. In general this means 1) the subject claims it themself, or 2) it is widely agreed on by scholars, or 3) is fictional and portrayed as such)
example: Trump claims to be of German descent.

name: basin country
description: country that have drainage to/from or border the body of water
example: The Congo Basin is located in several African countries.

name: subclass of
description: next higher class or type; all instances of these items are instances of those items; this item is a class (subset) of that item. Not to be confused with P31 (instance of)
example: A poodle is a subclass of the dog breed.

name: capital of
description: country, state, department, canton or other administrative division of which the municipality is the governmental seat
example: Madrid is the capital of Spain.

name: parent taxon
description: closest parent taxon of the taxon in question
example: Dogs and wolves belong to the parent taxon Canidae.

name: mother
description: female parent of the subject. For stepmother, use "stepparent" (P3448)
example: Beyonce's mother is Tina Knowles.

name: chairperson
description: presiding member of an organization, group or body
example: Sheryl Sandberg is the chairperson of Facebook.

name: end time
description: time an item ceases to exist or a statement stops being valid
example: The concert ends at 10:00 PM.

name: location of formation
description: location where a group or organization was formed
example: The band U2 formed in Dublin, Ireland.

name: narrative location
description: the narrative of the work is set in this location
example: The book Moby

name: replaced by
description: other person or item which continues the item by replacing it in its role. Use P156 (followed by) if the item is not replaced (e.g. books in a series), nor identical, but adds to the series without dropping the role of this item in that series
example: The iPhone 11 was replaced by the iPhone 12.

name: lyrics by
description: author of song lyrics
example: The song "Bohemian Rhapsody" has lyrics by Freddie Mercury.

name: territory claimed by
description: administrative divisions that claim control of a given area
example: China claims Taiwan as its territory.

name: product or material produced
description: material or product produced by a government agency, business, industry, facility, or process
example: Apple produces iPhones and MacBooks.

name: residence
description: the place where the person is or has been, resident
example: The White House is the residence of the U.S. President.

name: position held
description: subject currently or formerly holds the object position or public office
example: Angela Merkel held the position of Chancellor of Germany.

name: replaces
description: person, state or item replaced. Use "structure replaces" (P1398) for structures. Use "follows" (P155) if the previous item was not replaced or predecessor and successor are identical
example: The iPhone 12 replaces the iPhone 11.

name: influenced by
description: this person, idea, etc. is informed by that other person, idea, etc., e.g. “Heidegger was influenced by Aristotle”
example: The Beatles were influenced by Elvis Presley.

name: sister city
description: twin towns, sister cities, twinned municipalities and other localities that have a partnership or cooperative agreement, either legally or informally acknowledged by their governments
example: Paris and Berlin are sister cities.

name: separated from
description: subject was founded or started by separating from identified object
example: North Korea separated from South Korea in 1948.

name: unemployment rate
description: portion of a workforce population that is not employed
example: The unemployment rate in the United States is currently 6.0%.
